It‚Äôs that time of year again everyone where school bus safety needs to be reminded to all motorist. In Bainbridge Twp, school bus stops only occur on two lane roads. post_text:
Happy 67th Birthday, Kenston! On July 1, 1953, members of the Auburn and Bainbridge Boards of Education decided to consolidate the two districts and create the Kenston Local Schools. Their decision to merge was based on a successful trial school year in 1952, responsible financial management, growing enrollment in rural Geauga County and the ability to meet the educational needs of the students of Auburn and Bainbridge Townships.

Many things have changed in our communities and the world since Kenston‚Äôs consolidation in 1953, but our focus remains true. We continue to build on a foundation of continuous improvement and academic success.

Did you know? Kenston was chosen as the name of the new school district, taken from Kent‚Äôs Town, designating a small area in the early settlement that was common to both Auburn and Bainbridge Townships.

It's time to recognize the people that make Kenston amazing! This week's ‚≠êÔ∏è Shining Star Staff Members are the 2020 Retirees! ‚úàüéâ

‚≠ê Lenny Busta - Transportation (14 years of service)
‚≠ê Pat Fioritto - Special Education Teacher - Timmons (19 years of service at Kenston - 25 years total)
‚≠ê Gail Hastings - 3rd Grade Teacher - Timmons (23 years of service at Kenston - 30 years total)
‚≠ê Gary Kukelheim - Custodial/Maintenance Staff (29 years of service)
‚≠ê Terri Kempski - 1st Grade Teacher - Timmons (25 years of service)
‚≠ê Shelley Morehouse - 3rd Grade Teacher - Timmons (18 years of service at Kenston - 22 years total)
‚≠ê Allan Paradise - Transportation (7 years of service at Kenston - 49 years total)
‚≠ê Rich Vannoy - Grounds Department (30 years of service)

Your contributions to students and the entire Kenston community cannot be measured, and you will be missed! Thank you for all that you have done! Enjoy your retirement!

post_text: Proud to be a Kenston Bomber! ‚úàÔ∏è
shared_text:
Kenston Schools is feeling proud with Jeff Sypek and 2 others.
April 21 at 12:28 PM ¬∑

Congratulations to our students, staff and community! U.S. News and World Report 2020 Best High Schools highlighted Kenston as one of the top-performing public schools in Ohio and the country. We were ranked 6th in northeast Ohio, 22nd in the state and 598th nationally.

The rankings are based on state assessments in math and reading, graduation rates and how well students are prepared for college ‚Äì using Advanced Placement test data as the benchmark for success. It shows our focus on college and career readiness.

#besthighschool

post_text:
A reminder that tonight is Kenston Family Ties Night. There will be no homework and no events or activities after 4:30pm throughout the district. Please enjoy this time with your families by playing a game, cooking and/or eating together, reading a book or simply spending time together. We are thankful to the local businesses that have graciously offered special discounts or promotions to help you take advantage of this time together. Please click below for the list:

https://conta.cc/2VnzbKw

Also, be sure to share how you spent the evening and tag us in your Facebook or Twitter posts using the following hashtags:
#KENSTONFAMILYTIES
#GAMEONKENSTON

Those who participate will be entered into a drawing to receive a Game Night prize from Superintendent, Mrs. Nancy Santilli.
